<article>
    <h1>The lo&#xAD;gis&#xAD;tics of a vac&#xAD;ci&#xAD;na&#xAD;tion drive</h1>
    <h2>Pri&#xAD;vate health&#xAD;care group Park&#xAD;way Pan&#xAD;tai be&#xAD;gan vac&#xAD;ci&#xAD;nat&#xAD;ing its staff yes&#xAD;ter&#xAD;day. The group aims to give its staff the first of the two re&#xAD;quired doses of the Pfizer-BioN&#xAD;Tech vac&#xAD;cine within the next three weeks. Here is a look at what is be&#xAD;hind the process.</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210110/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-10"><time>2021-01-10</time></a>
        - <span>THE BIG STORY</span>
        - <span role="byline">TEXT: AU&#xAD;DREY TAN ST PHOTOS: ALPHON&#xAD;SUS CHERN SUN&#xAD;DAY TIMES GRAPH&#xAD;ICS</span>
    </section>

    <p>STEP 1 Gaug­ing sen­ti­ment</p>
    <p>• All staff will be in­di­vid­u­ally asked if they are in­ter­ested to re­ceive the Covid-19 vac­cine.</p>
    <p>• Based on this list, staff will be ros­tered to re­ceive the vac­cine.</p>
    <p>2 Or­der­ing the vac­cine</p>
    <p>• The mRNA vac­cine by Pfizer-BioN­Tech is tem­per­a­ture sen­si­tive, and must be stored at mi­nus 70 deg C to pre­vent it from de­grad­ing. Hos­pi­tals re­ceive thawed vials of the vac­cine, which must be used within five days.</p>
    <p>• Park­way Pan­tai will or­der the vac­cine doses from the Health Min­istry on a day-to-day ba­sis to re­duce waste for the ini­tial pe­riod.</p>
    <p>3 Re­ceiv­ing the vac­cine</p>
    <p>• Hos­pi­tals re­ceive the vac­cine doses the day be­fore they are ad­min­is­tered. The thawed vials are de­liv­ered in cooler boxes that are kept at a tem­per­a­ture of be­tween 2 and 8 deg C.</p>
    <p>• Once the hos­pi­tal’s phar­macy re­ceives the vac­cine doses, they are stored in a re­frig­er­a­tor.</p>
    <p>4 Ad­min­is­ter­ing the vac­cine</p>
    <p>• On the day of the vac­ci­na­tion, phar­ma­cists re­trieve the vac­cine vials from the re­frig­er­a­tor and place them in a phar­ma­ceu­ti­cal-grade in­su­lated bag along with some ice packs.</p>
    <p>• The bags are then trans­ported to the site where the vac­ci­na­tions are done, and im­me­di­ately placed into a re­frig­er­a­tor on-site. • Be­fore the vac­cine doses are ad­min­is­tered, the vials are left at room tem­per­a­ture un­til they reach 25 deg C. They are then di­luted. When this hap­pens, the vac­cine doses must be ad­min­is­tered within six hours.</p>
    <p>• As each vial con­tains five doses, staff are ros­tered to come in mul­ti­ples of five to pre­vent any doses from go­ing to waste.</p>
    <p>5 Mon­i­tor­ing pa­tients</p>
    <p>• Staff who go for the vac­ci­na­tions will have to stop by five sta­tions – reg­is­tra­tion, screening, vac­ci­na­tion, re­cov­ery and dis­charge.</p>
    <p>• At the screening stage, they fill in a ques­tion­naire which helps to de­ter­mine if they fall into cat­e­gories that should not yet re­ceive the vac­cine. Th­ese in­clude preg­nant women, those who may be se­verely im­muno­com­pro­mised and those with a his­tory of se­vere al­ler­gic re­ac­tions.</p>

